04421nam a22006015i 9781477313237DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20211968txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814773132377 a10.7560/7838432doi  a(DE-B1597)586634  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a863.641 aYáñez, Agustín, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Lean Lands /cAgustín Yáñez. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1968  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTRANSLATOR'S NOTE -- tCONTENTS -- tPART ONE—Betania: The Land or the Machine -- tGood morning and God bless you -- tKeep calm, don't be impatient -- tForward in the name of the cross -- tPART TWO—Jerusalen: The Return of Miguel Arcángel -- tStruggling along -- tTake your music somewhere else -- tLike a file of ants, the people -- tThere were shepherds in Belén -- tA man can have no worse enemy -- tThe storm winds had begun -- tPART FOUR—Babel: The Day of Judgment -- tThey stood gazing -- tThe clouds, the deceitful clouds -- tThere is no escape -- tPART FIVE—Damasco and Galilea: The Coming of Electricity -- tRelics of the past -- tNot forgotten for a single moment -- tSome of the things were credible -- tGod's will be done. Good night0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat was it that flew over with such a terrifying roar? Was it, as many said, the devil, or was it that thing a few had heard of, a flying machine? And those electric lights at Jacob Gallo’s farm, were they witchcraft or were they science? The theme of this harshly powerful novel is the impact of modern technology and ideas on a few isolated, tradition-bound hamlets in the aftermath of the Mexican Revolution of 1910. The old ways are represented by Epifanio Trujillo, the cacique of the region, now ailing and losing his grip on things; by ancient Madre Matiana, the region’s midwife, healer, counselor, and oracle; by penniless Rómulo and his wife Merced. “Progress” is represented by Don Epifanio’s bastard son Jacob, who acquired money and influence elsewhere during the Revolution and who now, against his father’s will, brings electricity, irrigation, fertilizers, and other modernities to the lean lands—together with armed henchmen. The conflict between the old and the new builds slowly and inexorably to a violent climax that will long remain in the reader’s memory. The author has given psychological and historical depth to his story by alternating the passages of narrative and dialogue with others in which several of the major characters brood on the past, the present, and the future. For instance, Matiana, now in her eighties, touchingly remembers how she was married and widowed before she had reached her seventeenth birthday. This dual technique is superbly handled, so that people and events have both a vivid actuality and an inner richness of meaning. The impact of the narrative is intensified by the twenty-one striking illustrations by Alberto Beltrán.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aFarmers-Mexico-Fiction. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/78384340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477313237423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477313237/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK